[2
Date: 20 Nov 2001
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: CNN, 20 Nov 2001 [edited
<http://www.cnn.com/2001/HEALTH/conditions/11/20/connecticut.anthrax/index.h
tml>

Anthrax suspected in elderly Connecticut patient
------------------------------------------------
Governor Rowland said the woman lives alone in her home in Oxford, about 10
miles west of New Haven. She seldom left the house and has no known
connection with the U.S. Postal Service. He described the woman as "a
patient who happens to be in her 90s, limited exposure in terms of
traveling, limited routine; so we're a little bit disturbed as to how this
could have happened."
"We thought it could have been natural anthrax, but that (occurs) only
through contact. This is inhaled anthrax, so that rules out natural
contact. So we really have no other leads at this point," he said.
The woman was admitted to Griffin Hospital last Wednesday with symptoms of
pneumonia, Rowland said. Three tests done at both the hospital in Derby and
in state health labs have indicated anthrax, the governor said. Clinical
samples are being flown to the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention
in Atlanta. Further results could come as early as Wednesday afternoon,
Rowland said. CDC investigators will also go to Derby and Oxford.
Rowland also said the woman's house has been secured and that FBI, state
police and health officials will do a preliminary examination of the house,
plan to retrace the woman's recent movements, and will interview her family.

